<p>(1) For the Schottky effect, the current density is controlled by the carriers injected into the medium by thermal excitation. The formula is as follows:
 <disp-formula id="FD6-materials-12-02657">
  <label>(6)</label>
  <math id="mm6">
   <mrow>
    <mrow>
     <mi>j</mi>
     <mo>=</mo>
     <mi>A</mi>
     <msup>
      <mi>T</mi>
      <mn>2</mn>
     </msup>
     <mo>·</mo>
     <mi>exp</mi>
     <mo stretchy="false">[</mo>
     <mo>−</mo>
     <mfrac>
      <mrow>
       <mi>φ</mi>
       <mo>−</mo>
       <msqrt>
        <mrow>
         <msup>
          <mi>e</mi>
          <mn>3</mn>
         </msup>
         <mi>E</mi>
         <mo>/</mo>
         <mn>4</mn>
         <mi>π</mi>
         <msub>
          <mi>ε</mi>
          <mn>0</mn>
         </msub>
         <msub>
          <mi>ε</mi>
          <mi>r</mi>
         </msub>
        </mrow>
       </msqrt>
      </mrow>
      <mrow>
       <mi>k</mi>
       <mi>T</mi>
      </mrow>
     </mfrac>
     <mo stretchy="false">]</mo>
    </mrow>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </disp-formula> where 
 <inline-formula>
  <math id="mm7">
   <mrow>
    <mrow>
     <msub>
      <mi>ε</mi>
      <mi>r</mi>
     </msub>
    </mrow>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </inline-formula> is the relative dielectric constant; 
 <inline-formula>
  <math id="mm8">
   <mrow>
    <mrow>
     <msub>
      <mi>ε</mi>
      <mn>0</mn>
     </msub>
    </mrow>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </inline-formula> is the vacuum dielectric constant; 
 <italic>A</italic> is the Richardson–Dushman constant; 
 <inline-formula>
  <math id="mm9">
   <mrow>
    <mi>φ</mi>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </inline-formula> is the work function of the metal.
</p>
